1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,000
A second person, Andy Snell.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Okay.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Today is Friday, the 22nd of July, 2011.

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:31,000
My name is Joe Manier of the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

6
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:39,000
I'm with our project videographer, John Bishop, and we're in Beacon, New York and delighted to be with Mr. Pete Seeger this morning to do an interview for the

7
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

8
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:57,000
John's going to make a quick adjustment.

9
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:04,000
He's moving a little laundry on the clothesline, and I think the change of the backdrop is a little...

10
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Okay, we're still worldwide.

11
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Mr. Seeger, great to be here and to visit with you.

12
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Well, thank you for coming all the way up here.

13
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Yeah, it's a pleasure. Nice to be here. It's a beautiful day. We got this beautiful view and it's lovely.

14
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:23,000
I thought I might ask since we're here in Beacon and place you've been for all these years, I thought I might ask you to recall if you could

15
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:34,000
have the Paul Robeson concert back in September of 1949 in peak skill, where I think you opened with a few songs and it was quite a day as I understand.

16
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:51,000
I realized only a year or two ago that that attack on the Robeson concert, they were actually two of them, August 27th and September 4th.

17
00:01:51,000 --> 00:02:02,000
You may have saved America from a full-fledged fascism, whatever J. Edgar Hoover could put into effect.

18
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:16,000
He had concentration camps already up for about 12,000 people, but he had been unable to persuade Congress and Truman to pass the necessary law to let him fill them.

19
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:23,000
I was probably one of the people he was going to put there.

20
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:35,000
In July of 1949, Truman sent one of his high officials. I think it was the Secretary of State up to peak skill and spoke to the American Legion.

21
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:43,000
He said, this man Robeson loves Russia. He hates America. He's coming here to sing.

22
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:53,000
I'm sure you know what to do, and he went back to Washington. In other words, he gave him the green light to do whatever they wanted.

23
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:06,000
50 years later, I learned more about what happened then because the Robeson Foundation had a press conference in on September 4th, 1999.

24
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:14,000
People came for telling what they knew of the event 50 years before.

25
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:22,000
A man in his 60s said, I was a teenager then, and I was talking with some friends on the sidewalk.

26
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:32,000
When a truck pulls up and a policeman gets out, he says, you all get in the truck. We're going down to Arseneen Beach and collect stones to throw at the commas.

27
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:39,000
So it was not a great big secret.

28
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Now, I'm told that the police force, as well as the American Legion, were infiltrated by extreme right people.

29
00:03:51,000 --> 00:04:00,000
There was a Klucluck's clan chapter just a few miles south of here, and there were others down nearer to peak skill.

30
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:11,000
There were also some German Americans from Lake Valhalla, who had never really gone along with the war against Hitler.

31
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:22,000
Right after the attack, bumper stickers went up.

32
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:32,000
There were signs about 20 inches wide saying, wake up America and under peak skill did.

33
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:38,000
And in Europe, they said, that's the same sign that went up after Crystal Nocht.

34
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Wake up Germany Munich did, or wherever Crystal Nocht started.

35
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:51,000
And they'd all been printed in advance, and they went up right away.

36
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Interestingly enough, they all disappeared just as quickly as they went up, about five weeks later.

37
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And no one has been able to find exactly where the order came, but it was obviously an order from somewhere high up.

38
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And now, I think they found out that it had backfired on them.

39
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:24,000
People all over the country saw those hate-filled faces.

40
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And on TV, you could hear them, shout, go back to Russia, kite, nigger lovers, wham.

41
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:48,000
And there was an ugly scene, and they found now Truman needed to sell J.A. Duhuver.

42
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:54,000
No, that kind of thing doesn't go in America.

43
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:59,000
Let me take you to a place that had a very different spirit about it.

44
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:05,000
I think in 57, 58 you would make various visits to Islander.

45
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:10,000
What do you and I visited there because Alan Lomax told us about the place?

46
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:21,000
And when we went west to visit his family, out in Oklahoma and Texas, we stopped him to say hello.

47
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And the photograph that was taken of me playing the banjo, and listening to Woody playing the guitar, that was taken there in 1940.

48
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:45,000
And in 1957, it was the 25th anniversary of the founding of Highlander,

49
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Boer-Zilphia, Miles Horton's wife, Zilphia Horton.

50
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:59,000
And I guess you know it's spelled Z-I-P-H-I-A.

51
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:07,000
She was killed by drinking some poison cleaning fluid, I think.

52
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:14,000
And I got a phone call, I think, from Miles Heng-Pee.

53
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Can you come down here?

54
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:21,000
It's the 25th anniversary of Highlander, we can't have an anniversary without music.

55
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And without Zilphia here, would you come down, sing a few songs?

56
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:36,000
So I went there and King and Abernathy and Rosa drove up from Montgomery,

57
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:41,000
and King gave us a short speech.

58
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:49,000
And afterwards, we all were photographed in front of the barn,

59
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:57,000
along with a curious Horton Miles teenage daughter.

60
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:03,000
And that photograph has been well used.

61
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:10,000
That's the first of time I ever met King.

62
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:16,000
Only other time I met him was a year before he was assassinated.

63
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:23,000
I was asked to sing a few songs at a big peace rally outside the United Nations.

64
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
I just had been 80,000 people there.

65
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:32,000
And I think it was the only day after that he had spoken at Riverside Church.

66
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
And he probably said essentially, the same things, maybe a little shorter.

67
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:42,000
I saw a black car inching its way through the huge crowd and heard people whispering,

68
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
he's here, he's here.

69
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:49,000
And the black car got about 20 feet from the speaker stand.

70
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:54,000
It took six men to hold the crowd away so they could open the door

71
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:01,000
and push their way towards, took about five minutes to go that 20 feet.

72
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:06,000
And I wondered how can a person live with this kind of adulation?

73
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:12,000
And that's where I heard him say, I have to face the fact that my country

74
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:17,000
is the greatest pervert of violence in the world.

75
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:20,000
I must get out of the ad-man.

76
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:26,000
I'm sure that LBJ just lost his temper then.

77
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:32,000
He said, after all I did for that guy, now look what he does to me.

78
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:38,000
He just got boiling mad and finally he slams his fist down and picks up the phone.

79
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
Whoever do what you want.

80
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,000
Are those thoughts for a past?

81
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:49,000
Sure, John's gonna have us pause for a moment.

82
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:57,000
With my reading one morning in the New York Times,

83
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:04,000
a tiny little two-inch piece on the back pages saying that there was a bus boycott

84
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,000
in Montgomery, Alabama.

85
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:14,000
And I somehow got in touch with the reporter and said, can you give me the address of the people behind the boycott?

86
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:20,000
And he gave me the address of the Montgomery Improvement Association.

87
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:30,000
And I called up and got ED Nixon on the phone.

88
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:38,000
He was the person that Rosa called when she was arrested and she was allowed to make one phone call.

89
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:47,000
And he said, Rosa, I'll be right down to pick you up, but he said, this is what we need.

90
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:56,000
That teenager that tried to stand up to the police was pregnant.

91
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:00,000
And we couldn't have gotten the community behind her.

92
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:03,000
Everybody knows Rosa.

93
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:10,000
And don't know the details.

94
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:16,000
But he also knew that King was a fantastic speaker.

95
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:21,000
And he called up, I found this out later.

96
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And he called up King and said, could we hold a protest meeting at your church?

97
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:34,000
And King says, well, I'm new here, brother Nixon.

98
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:38,000
And let me check with my deacons to make sure they approve.

99
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:41,000
Call me back in two hours.

100
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And two hours later, Nixon called up.

101
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
I'm glad to say, brother Nixon, that the deacons approve.

102
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:53,000
You may have the meeting at our church tonight.

103
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:05,000
And Nixon says, Reverend King, I'm so glad you said that because I've just told 200 people we are meeting at eight o'clock.

104
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
Oh, it's a good thing the deacons said, yes.

105
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And that's when he made that most important statement, probably several times.

106
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:25,000
We will win this buscot boycott if we are nonviolent.

107
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:32,000
And I'm sure he had to reiterate this in the future weeks.

108
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:42,000
There might be some doctors or lawyers, African-Americans, who's business was going to be hurt.

109
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:48,000
And Dr. King, we can make a few compromises.

110
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:52,000
But if we, this will lead to trouble.

111
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:55,000
And we don't want to see violence.

112
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:00,000
And he said, what are you doing tonight?

113
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
Can we discuss this?

114
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:12,000
And because he'd already gotten phone calls from angry young people said, look, they've tried to kill us.

115
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,000
And they've beaten us.

116
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
Why do we do something to them?

117
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:21,000
And he would say, are you free tonight?

118
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:23,000
We have to talk this over.

119
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:34,000
And he'd put these two groups of African-Americans facing each other and say, we have to solve this problem.

120
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:38,000
And he didn't need to do too much talking.

121
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:44,000
But they had to each state the position and listen to the other.

122
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:49,000
And finally came to a compromise.

123
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:55,000
They would continue, but they would try and find ways.

124
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:56,000
There'd be no violence.

125
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:04,000
And then, of course, this man should be given more credit in the civil rights movement.

126
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:08,000
Bull Connor.

127
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,000
I knew his name in 1940.

128
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
I was hitchhiking through the South.

129
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
And people said, you're going through Birmingham.

130
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:16,000
Stay out of the way of Bull Connor.

131
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:18,000
He's the police chief.

132
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:25,000
And I was staying with a man who'd been beaten up very badly, Joe Gulder.

133
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:31,000
And he also knew, stay out of the way of Bull Connor.

134
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,000
He lived about 12 miles north.

135
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,000
Seven miles north.

136
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
I think he's 12 miles north, and I stayed with him.

137
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:46,000
And his teenage daughter, Marjorie.

138
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:50,000
She later on married her man, named Franz, Marjorie Franz.

139
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:53,000
And I think she only recently died.

140
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:56,000
Wonderful person.

141
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:01,000
But Bull Connor had lots to do with.

142
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:09,000
Well, he was in effect the mayor because he had his own people.

143
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:14,000
And Marjorie finally told him what to do.

144
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:31,000
And it was he using violence that really opened the eyes of the country of how terrible that whole system down there was.

145
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:35,000
We have neighbors here.

146
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:42,000
And we didn't realize things like this could happen in America.

147
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:49,000
When they saw the Hoses pointed at the people rolling around on the ground,

148
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:54,000
and they were trying to keep the Hose from hitting their face.

149
00:15:54,000 --> 00:16:01,000
And the dogs biting the children.

150
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:04,000
And that was Bull Connor's work.

151
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:12,000
I wanted to ask about another element of your visit to Highlander in 1957 when you met Reverend King.

152
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:18,000
Reverend Abernathy and Rose Parks for the first time was I think that may have been the occasion that they first heard you play.

153
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:20,000
We shall overcome.

154
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
I didn't know how to play it right.

155
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
But I did sing it.

156
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:37,000
Zilvia had taught me the song when she was north in 1946, I believe, almost 10 years earlier.

157
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:49,000
And I printed it in our little song magazine, People's Songs.

158
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
I didn't print it right.

159
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:02,000
What really made the song spread was Guy Caravan and Frank Hamilton learning to put it in a special kind of rhythm.

160
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:05,000
It's called 12-8-time.

161
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:09,000
You know when you have four beats per measure.

162
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:13,000
And if you want to make the notes fast, you usually double them.

163
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:19,000
You get a 1, 2, 3, 4, 1, 2, 3, and 4.

164
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:25,000
But 12-8-time means that you triple each one of those beats.

165
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:29,000
One to T, one to T, one to T, one to T, one to T, one to T, one to T.

166
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:34,000
And I had known the time.

167
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,000
I used it when I sing Jacob's Ladder.

168
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:42,000
We are climbing.

169
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:48,000
Jacob's Ladder.

170
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:51,000
So it was not unknown to me.

171
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:59,000
But Frank Hamilton and Guy Caravan, Guy Caravan, I hope you get the spelling right.

172
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:09,000
Way back in 1960, before that, had been learning gospel songs at local Baptist church.

173
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:19,000
And we got into these subtle variations in rhythm.

174
00:18:19,000 --> 00:18:29,000
Rhythm is such an important part of African American music as cities, of course, in African music.

175
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:34,000
A song isn't a song unless you know it and get the rhythm right.

176
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:42,000
You might have the melody exactly right, but if you don't have the rhythm right, you don't have the song right.

177
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:52,000
But I think I remember where you have written that Anne Braden was there as well as she was driving Dr. King after that 57 meeting.

178
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,000
That's right.

179
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:57,000
She drove him north and going through Tennessee.

180
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:00,000
I see your members sitting in the back seat.

181
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
We shall overcome. That song really sticks with you, doesn't it?

182
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:14,000
I didn't sing it a great deal, but I sang it more.

183
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:24,000
And then in 1960, Guy Caravan was the full time man in charge of music at Highlander.

184
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:31,000
And he decided to have a weekend called Singing in the Movement.

185
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:43,000
And there were people, mostly young people, from Maine, pardon me, from Texas, to Florida, to Virginia.

186
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:49,000
They came from all over. But there must have been about 50 or 60 people there.

187
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:52,000
They raised the money for the fair somehow.

188
00:19:52,000 --> 00:20:02,000
And we sang from Friday evening all through Saturday and ended finally going home on Sunday.

189
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:14,000
And we shall overcome was the hit of the weekend with that new rhythm.

190
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:26,000
It was about five weeks later when the organization was started in Raleigh, North Carolina for young people.

191
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:28,000
Now you tell me the exact name.

192
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:29,000
Snake.

193
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:30,000
Snake.

194
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:34,000
Student, nonviolent, coordinating committee.

195
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:42,000
And somebody shouted from the crowd, Guy, teach us all we shall overcome.

196
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
And he did.

197
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:49,000
And that's when they adopted the idea of cross your hands.

198
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:54,000
And your right hand grasps the left hand of the person to your left.

199
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And your left hand grasps the right hand of the person to your right.

200
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
And you're closer together, your shoulders touch.

201
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:05,000
You sway slowly from right to left.

202
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:11,000
And this also is a great African tradition.

203
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:16,000
And you move your body when you sing.

204
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:21,000
You don't just sing no matter how a glorious voice you have, you sing.

205
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:29,000
And you get harmony.

206
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:37,000
And it was three years later I was able to give a concert in Carnegie Hall

207
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:42,000
before taking my family overseas.

208
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:56,000
We visited 35 countries around the world across the Pacific, Australia, then up to Indonesia, then to Japan, where Toshi's father accompanied us.

209
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And saw his own family that he had not visited for 50 years.

210
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:11,000
And his older sister kneeled down with her head touching the concrete and would not rise until he said, please rise sister.

211
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:16,000
He was the oldest male in the family.

212
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:19,000
And many of his brothers and sisters had died.

213
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:24,000
And of course his parents were a died.

214
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:32,000
But anyway, that carnival concert I got a number of my neighbors here in Beacon.

215
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:37,000
Black and white.

216
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:41,000
To come down.

217
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:45,000
I guess I must have paid their fair.

218
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:54,000
And I had in the afternoon a rehearsal with him said, some sat on my left, some sat on my right.

219
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:58,000
Nobody sat in the back all they'd see was my rear end.

220
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:12,000
And I said, if you get the answer back in the harmony, you know answer back is such an important part of African American music.

221
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:18,000
Whether it's pop songs or jazz or gospel songs.

222
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:25,000
One voice answering another.

223
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:44,000
And so if I said if you get the answer back right and there'll be mics on you as well as on me, then I think we'll get this audience singing.

224
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:53,000
And the Columbia Record Company shelt out the cash.

225
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:57,000
You know, it's not a nice story to tell.

226
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:08,000
But you know if you want to record at Carnegie, you have to pay $100,000 to the stage crew.

227
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:15,000
They're union members and this is the union rules.

228
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:20,000
$100,000 if you want it.

229
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:24,000
So Columbia had Rick and John Hammond Jr.

230
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:26,000
He was quite an extraordinary man.

231
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:33,000
I didn't find out until recently he was the great grandson of Cornelius Vanderbilt.

232
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:38,000
His mother was a granddaughter of it.

233
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:45,000
But she'd gotten religion and hardly looked at her son so he was raised by servants.

234
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:57,000
And as a teenager would go down south and listen to street singers and so on.

235
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:02,000
And he had the music where he found Brownie McGee and Sonny Terry.

236
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:12,000
And he had them sing at the concert he put on to raise money for all things, the new masses, the Communist magazine.

237
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:21,000
In 1938, I was up in Cambridge, Massachusetts, that's in my last few weeks at Harvard.

238
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:27,000
The concert was called From Spirituals to Swing.

239
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:32,000
I think Count Basie's orchestra was there, but I may be wrong.

240
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:35,000
It might have been another swing band.

241
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:41,000
And he had a variety of extraordinary musicians.

242
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:46,000
So he put up the money for the...

243
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:48,000
So my Hammond put up the money?

244
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:50,000
Columbia.

245
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
Well, that Spirituals to Swing, I think John Hammond raised that separately.

246
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:59,000
That was for the new massacres.

247
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:09,000
And my concert was in 1963 and I was briefly a Columbia recording artist.

248
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:16,000
Was that your appearance at Carnegie were the freedom singers with you on that occasion?

249
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:19,000
I'm not sure.

250
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:26,000
My memory isn't good, but they might have been with me because it was in 60, I believe,

251
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:34,000
that Bernice was expelled from the local college in Albany, Georgia.

252
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:38,000
And...

253
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,000
Now, wait a minute, wait a minute.

254
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:42,000
You were in Albany in 62.

255
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,000
Yeah.

256
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:45,000
And I didn't do a very good job.

257
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
Why do you say it into the job?

258
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:56,000
I said, you should know that all kinds of people have different kinds of songs.

259
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:03,000
And I said, for example, white people came over here with old ballads from England.

260
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:06,000
And I sang them some English ballads.

261
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:14,000
And somebody leaned over to Cordell Regan, who was later married, Bernice.

262
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:22,000
He said, if this is white folks music, I have to say I don't think much of it.

263
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:26,000
So you didn't get quite the crowd response that you thought you might down there

264
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:32,000
and addressing all these civil rights, SNCC folks down in Albany.

265
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:35,000
But you out of that came your relationship with Bernice Johnson?

266
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:38,000
That's exactly right.

267
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:49,000
She and Cordell and that tall man who now lives in Kentucky, a good songwriter.

268
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:54,000
And another man that I can't remember their names.

269
00:27:54,000 --> 00:28:05,000
I'd gone to the office of in Atlanta and said, you know,

270
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:17,000
just like the Fisk Jubilee singers, that singers, these singers could raise a lot of money for you traveling around.

271
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:22,000
And that's when they started the Freedom Singers.

272
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:29,000
And in 63, Toshin I was getting ready to go overseas.

273
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:36,000
I think we left in late July, went to Hawaii first.

274
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:42,000
Or maybe we went to the West Coast, sang in California, and then Hawaii.

275
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:51,000
And then went on across the Pacific, stopped at Samoa, two Samoas.

276
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:57,000
And then Dora Australia and so on.

277
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:03,000
And sang for our supper, as I said, over 30 countries.

278
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:09,000
But Toshin had the names and addresses of all the colleges I'd been singing to.

279
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:20,000
So it's matter just a couple days' work to send out letters or recordings maybe.

280
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:30,000
And the Freedom Singers to large numbers could have been over 100, see.

281
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:38,000
And gave them the address or the telephone number of Bernice.

282
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:42,000
So Toshin set up their first tour.

283
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:53,000
And that's why you were two later, Bernice named her daughter Toshy.

284
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:56,000
Toshy is the best organizer in the family.

285
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:03,000
I'm, uh, get lots of ideas, but I'm not a good organizer.

286
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:12,000
When you came back from that long overseas tour, by summer of 64, you were in Mississippi.

287
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
I guess so.

288
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
I've forgotten where exactly.

289
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:21,000
Places like Hattiesburg and, and, uh, Meridian.

290
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:26,000
I met Bill Kunstler in the Arab, Arab plane.

291
00:30:26,000 --> 00:30:31,000
And we landed at Jackson, Mississippi.

292
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:39,000
I remember when I was singing a couple of things I saw the body of the man in the seat in front of me, stiffen.

293
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:45,000
As though he was probably outraged at some of the things I was saying.

294
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:51,000
And sure enough, he was waiting for us in the anti-rum outside the airport.

295
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:56,000
There's a little place where people take off their overcoats or whatever.

296
00:30:56,000 --> 00:31:02,000
And I mean, he said, you come down here to sing for the niggers.

297
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:07,000
I said, I hope I can sing for everybody who wants to hear me.

298
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:10,000
He said, well, well, you better watch your step.

299
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:14,000
If we weren't here, I'd knock the shit out of you.

300
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:18,000
But there was a look magazine reporter with me.

301
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:23,000
And I didn't guess he didn't know exactly where he's from.

302
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:28,000
So I was saved that time.

303
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:40,000
And I might have been in danger, but I did what I was told.

304
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:48,000
I went down two or three times, as I remember.

305
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:56,000
I was singing to about 200 people in a church when they gave me a piece of paper.

306
00:31:56,000 --> 00:32:04,000
So they found the bodies of Goodman, Schwerner, and Cheney.

307
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:08,000
And I made this announcement.

308
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
There was no shouting.

309
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:16,000
There was no anger.

310
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:21,000
So lips moving in prayer.

311
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:33,000
And I think I sang the song that Fred Hellman made up, oh, healing river, send down your waters.

312
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:36,000
Send down your waters upon this land.

313
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:46,000
And Fred Macoff wrote the words up in Long Island, and Fred put the melody of it.

314
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:54,000
It's a beautiful song.

315
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:00,000
Any other things stand out when you think back to Mississippi in that freedom summer?

316
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:13,000
I don't know whether that summer of when, but after the killings in Selma,

317
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:24,000
when they tried to have a march to Montgomery, they ended up getting permission, formal permission.

318
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:31,000
And they said there would be helicopters overhead to make sure it was safe.

319
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:34,000
And Toshin, I were invited.

320
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:39,000
In fact, I have kept a copy of the telegram from King.

321
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:44,000
The federal government and the courts have spoken.

322
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:50,000
And we will march from Selma to Montgomery on such and such a date.

323
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:54,000
And we answered back, said, we're coming.

324
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:57,000
We actually didn't start from the center of Selma.

325
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:00,000
I think it was a mile or so outside of town.

326
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:07,000
And we joined about 300 people, I'd say, maybe more.

327
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:12,000
And it was raining half the time.

328
00:34:12,000 --> 00:34:16,000
King and other people were up in the front.

329
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:22,000
We were about halfway down.

330
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:31,000
I remember Harry Belafonte standing by the side at one and urging us on.

331
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:39,000
Oh, you'd find out that the new way of singing, we shall overcome.

332
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:47,000
That was the first time I heard it that way.

333
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:50,000
Not everybody liked We shall overcome.

334
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:56,000
The great playwright, what's her name now?

335
00:34:56,000 --> 00:34:59,000
She wrote Broadway hits.

336
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:03,000
She says, someday, someday, that's been said too long.

337
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:08,000
Lily and Helman.

338
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:15,000
And probably there were others who felt this way at any rate.

339
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:19,000
We'd sing We shall overcome right after it, somebody would shout, what do we want?

340
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:23,000
And the whole crowd would shout at the top of their lungs.

341
00:35:23,000 --> 00:35:26,000
Freedom! When do we want it?

342
00:35:26,000 --> 00:35:29,000
Now!

343
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:36,000
And that took away the softness of, someday, someday, someday.

344
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:46,000
And I remember the helicopters overhead flying over the cornfields on either side.

345
00:35:46,000 --> 00:35:55,000
So to watch for somebody with a rifle.

346
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:58,000
Let's take a little break for a minute.

347
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:01,000
Just like that on the river.

348
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:09,000
I have a song 50, say, on Newberg Bay waiting for the wind and tide.

349
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:16,000
They couldn't get past stormking until the tide changed or the wind.

350
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:24,000
But with both the wind and tide against them, they're making a pretty good time.

351
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:29,000
She was pretty.

352
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:32,000
I don't know when you just know if that's clear water.

353
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:34,000
Sure, yeah, that is the clear water.

354
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:36,000
It's sleeping in the river.

355
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:42,000
Don McLean wrote, by Miss America Pie, at a local clear water fundraiser.

356
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:45,000
Is that an arrow? Is that an arrow? Is that an arrow?

357
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:48,000
Look at Chevy, is it the living?

358
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:53,000
Yeah.

359
00:36:53,000 --> 00:37:00,000
You had mentioned earlier the vivid recollection of the big rally at the UN

360
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:06,000
where Reverend King had given the address just the day after Riverside.

361
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:18,000
And, um, Lack Doctor King, you really thought about these issues of social justice in a fashion

362
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:26,000
that brought these concerns together as one common broad arena of effort,

363
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:33,000
nonviolence, anti-war, environment, social justice, racial equality.

364
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:36,000
I'm interested in your thoughts about, and women.

365
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:38,000
And women, certainly. Yeah.

366
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:58,000
I'm interested in your thoughts about the late 60s in the United States and thinking of the shift towards the way SNCC came a part a little bit.

367
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:01,000
The movement took a different direction.

368
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:11,000
Dr. King began to lift his voice on economic and foreign policy issues.

369
00:38:11,000 --> 00:38:18,000
Yes.

370
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:27,000
King undoubtedly knew that he'd be assassinated by some local person or somebody high up.

371
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:36,000
And that's why he gave that final speech.

372
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:46,000
He knew he didn't have long, and, uh, and saying now, in effect, he was saying,

373
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:59,000
you have to pick up the torch.

374
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:04,000
Nobody knows if there'll be a human race here in a hundred years.

375
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:14,000
Kurt Vonnegut, uh, was so pessimistic, he didn't think there would be a human race here.

376
00:39:14,000 --> 00:39:21,000
I tell people, I think we have a 50-50 chance.

377
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:32,000
I think if we are still here, it will be large numbers, whether it's hundreds of thousands or millions,

378
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:38,000
I don't know, of small things that do it.

379
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:47,000
A few people sitting in an office somewhere, more likely, a few people,

380
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:53,000
uh, doing something together locally.

381
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:58,000
For example, a woman here in this town of Beacon,

382
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:06,000
had a tried in several ways, bringing black and white together.

383
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:16,000
And she, her husband was dead, and she was retired,

384
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:22,000
but she got together with some other women and said, there should be a one day a year

385
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:30,000
when the mainstream could be closed and we'll have been called the Spirit of Beacon Day.

386
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:42,000
They invited the charge ten dollars for any organization they wanted to get about 12 feet along the sidewalk,

387
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:53,000
to put up a table, and they could sell food, or they could play a record, or have a piece of paper.

388
00:40:53,000 --> 00:41:02,000
They called up first, I think, 24 churches, white and black, and Latino,

389
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:08,000
and conservative and radical.

390
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:18,000
And so they were on, and then they had the middle class organizations

391
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:24,000
that Kewanaus, the Lions, the American Legion,

392
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:33,000
and they also invited our little Beacon Clearwater Club, this Beacon Slope Club.

393
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:44,000
And, uh, at 12 o'clock, the police set up barriers,

394
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:56,000
and if you wanted to go east to west or west to east, you had to leave Main Street and go down one of the side streets.

395
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:05,000
And the first time it was done, they had a few hundred people there, and next year it was twice as many.

396
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:15,000
And next year it was twice as many now, I think now about two-thirds of the town is there, like 10,000 people are there.

397
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:21,000
And there's dancing going on, and different kinds of music.

398
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:29,000
And I think I'll be down there with my friends, helping the kids group.

399
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:35,000
They're now 11-year-olds, they started when they were nine-year-olds.

400
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:42,000
Maybe they're 12 now, they call themselves the River Town Kids.

401
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:49,000
And they're not only singing some of the songs, I taught them, but they're making up new songs.

402
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:54,000
And they're singing some old songs.

403
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:03,000
And by one, I think by 12-30, they have a parade in the beginning.

404
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:07,000
It was just the fire engine and the ambulance.

405
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:11,000
But next year is the fire engine, the ambulance, and some people.

406
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:18,000
Now the parade is an hour long, and everybody wants to be in the parade.

407
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:25,000
And after the parade, then is when they improvise.

408
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:42,000
In fact, some women from a Hindu temple, now beautifully colored saris, they're dancing on a platform with a tape recording of music from India.

409
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:57,000
And 200 people watching in the minute applauding to think that this was a narrow-minded little factory town until I guess World War II.

410
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:05,000
It started with a Dutch girl.

411
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:11,000
I don't know why this isn't Dutch or something. Well, in a way, it's...

412
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:31,000
The same thing that produced the Civil Rights Movement, people of different backgrounds getting together, like Violeta Liu's whole was Italian American, mother of five, I'm told, and she came down from Detroit.

413
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:37,000
And wrist getting assassinated and didn't get assassinated.

414
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:44,000
Here in Beacon, nobody got assassinated, but I know what sparked it off.

415
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:53,000
Yes, it was sparked off because there was a high school race riot.

416
00:44:53,000 --> 00:45:05,000
There was a high school race riot, and these women decided, let's get people in, they started with the churches, and the respectable groups.

417
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:14,000
Now literally anybody can... Yet the town is a town of 14,000, but 10,000 of them, right there.

418
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:23,000
Of course, some are grumbling, oh, this town's going to hell, but the kids are saying, yeah, it's fun, dad, you oughta come down.

419
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:28,000
Let me ask a final question for me, John may have questions as well.

420
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:48,000
I'm just interested in what you think these days about our situation. Here we have our first black president, and yet we're embroiled in complicated and long-running war, and I'm just curious about your perspective thinking about this long arc of history.

421
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:56,000
Well, we know that it would be compromises. I didn't think he would make so many.

422
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:11,000
However, I'm not a great politician, and it might be that those are the kind of compromises that have to be made.

423
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:30,000
On the other hand, I think if I had my brains about me, the one time I did see Obama and his wife when I sang that, when I led the crowd in singing this land as your land, I say,

424
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:56,000
don't try, I would have said, don't try and get reelected in 2012. Do the best job you possibly can, and you will get reelected in 2016, because there'll be such a contrast between what you do and what they do in 2012.

425
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:07,000
As it is, he may very possibly won't get reelected, which is a sea. He didn't make enough compromises, and that won't be the lesson.

426
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:25,000
Yes, I could have done that. I did speak to him all of ten seconds. He said to me, Mr. Seeger, my mother played me a records at age four.

427
00:47:26,000 --> 00:47:38,000
I said, don't try and get elected in 2012, and you will get reelected in 2016.

428
00:47:40,000 --> 00:47:41,000
This is a reaction.

429
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:46,000
I should have said that. I should have said that, but I didn't.

430
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:53,000
There are a lot of times you should have said something, and it comes out after the moment.

431
00:47:53,000 --> 00:48:01,000
Well, you've said so much through your music, and otherwise, and it has sort of picked up and carried our history along. It's a real honor and a privilege to be with you. Thank you.

432
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:14,000
Well, thank you, and I'm glad to hear that you're going to help this nation remember that extraordinary man.

433
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:25,000
He had only 13 years to do what he could do. Of course, Lincoln only had five years.

434
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:29,000
Thank you.

435
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:37,000
Oh, let me tell you another story about what you'd be interested. Maybe this could help you.

436
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:53,000
I always thought that Ruthiford B. Hayes was the worst president we ever had, because he allowed the troops to go back north,

437
00:48:53,000 --> 00:49:09,000
and after the Civil War, and didn't try to push through the changes with troops down there.

438
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:20,000
Incidentally, the song Michael Rowe the Boulder Shore was in a book called Slave Song, written by an officer,

439
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:29,000
a Northern officer who was stationed in Georgia, Southeast Georgia.

440
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:42,000
But there had been a lot of scandals in Grant's second administration. Grant was fairly honest, I believe,

441
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:54,000
but the people he was told to appoint were not. And there was one scandal after another after another after another after another in his second term.

442
00:49:54,000 --> 00:50:03,000
And the Republicans felt sure they wouldn't not get reelected unless they found somebody squeaky clean.

443
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:15,000
They found it in the Governor of Ohio, Ruthiford B. Hayes, who had had an absolutely impeccable history in Ohio.

444
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:30,000
And they said when they were running, it was a dead tie in the Electoral College.

445
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:36,000
And then the election was thrown into the House, and again it was a dead tie.

446
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:48,000
And Republicans found one Democrat who would vote for Hayes if he would withdraw federal troops from the South.

447
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:57,000
And it's possible that Hayes might have said, well, I could resign right now, but then they'd do it anyway.

448
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:02,000
And he was a lawyer. He felt this kind of job should be done by talking anyway, not by guns.

449
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:10,000
He knew the Governor of Louisiana, and they both agreed if they had schools or ex-slaves.

450
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:17,000
Sooner or later they'd all be voting again. But the Ku Klux Klan was too strong.

451
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:25,000
And so he was out of office. However, he liked to make speeches.

452
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:34,000
And he'd jump into one of these, had this new invention called a rail road, and he gave a speech somewhere.

453
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:41,000
Eight years after he was out of office, the Supreme Court made a very important decision.

454
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:46,000
They said there's no capital punishment for corporations.

455
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:51,000
Up until that time, the state could hand give out a charter.

456
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:57,000
And if they didn't like what the corporation was doing, they could take the charter away.

457
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:06,000
But not after 1888. And Ruthford behave made a speech somewhere.

458
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:10,000
Face it, we no longer have a government of the people, by the people, for the people.

459
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:15,000
We have a government of corporations, by corporations, for corporations.

460
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:23,000
Way back then, only radicals made that kind of a statement.

461
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:33,000
Farmers trying to get better deal for farmers or unions trying to get a better deal from the job.

462
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:37,000
Yeah, indeed. I'm thinking of the invention farmers.

463
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:44,000
You did early work with music and puppet theater around farm strikes here in the valley.

464
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:56,000
Half a mile from where we're sitting was a radical summer camp for put together mainly by Jewish garment workers.

465
00:52:56,000 --> 00:53:02,000
And it was called Camp Nitt Gidiget, meaning no worry in Yiddish.

466
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:05,000
Way back in the 20s.

467
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:11,000
But in the 30s, they decided to make some compromise that they call it Camp Beacon.

468
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:17,000
And I and three others had put together a little puppet troupe.

469
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:20,000
And we had some funny things.

470
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And we also had a skit where Governor Dewey has cut the education budget.

471
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:35,000
And now without sufficient education, Pinocchio gets in trouble.

472
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:42,000
And we also had a skit we'd written about farmers not getting paid enough.

473
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:48,000
And through enough in August, the dairy farmers union went on strike.

474
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:52,000
And we had a skit already for it.

475
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:55,000
The farmer is milking the cow and he says, I don't know what to do.

476
00:53:55,000 --> 00:54:02,000
My wife has taken the children and left she says I can't afford to feed him anymore.

477
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:06,000
But they were only paying me two cents a quart from milk.

478
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:11,000
They were selling it in New York for twelve cents a quart.

479
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:16,000
Somebody's making some money.

480
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:19,000
And the cow says, well, you're very foolish.

481
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:23,000
Not together, get together with the other farmers.

482
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:29,000
If you all stick together, you will be able to demand a better price.

483
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:32,000
So the cow was the union organizer.

484
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:36,000
And I played the part of the cow up there.

485
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:39,000
They were hand puppets.

486
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:42,000
And we went from strike meeting to strike meeting.

487
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:46,000
It was exciting.

488
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:49,000
And we didn't charge money for it.

489
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:51,000
We passed the hat.

490
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:54,000
And they didn't have much money.

491
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:57,000
But they'd give us a nickel or a dime.

492
00:54:57,000 --> 00:55:03,000
And some people even a quarter, which was a lot of money then.

493
00:55:03,000 --> 00:55:05,000
I was probably like five dollars.

494
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:11,000
And nickel was an ice cream cone or a Hershey bar.

495
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:15,000
That's what it was back then.

496
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:19,000
Do you know how that was a wonderful thing?

497
00:55:19,000 --> 00:55:21,000
Let me think.

498
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:25,000
Oh, do you know Stacey White in Mississippi?

499
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:32,000
Well, she has an annual get together to remember Fannie Lou Hamer

500
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:39,000
and the things that went on back in those days.

501
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:42,000
I've got her telephone number in there.

502
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:46,000
So before you leave.

503
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:48,000
I'm not sure when.

504
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:50,000
I don't think it's in the dead of summer.

505
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:52,000
I think it's in the spring.

506
00:55:52,000 --> 00:55:54,000
But it might be in the fall.

507
00:55:54,000 --> 00:55:56,000
And you've attended?

508
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:58,000
No, I've never attended.

509
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:02,000
But I've sent contributions to them.

510
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:08,000
Any thought about Miss Hanger?

511
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:12,000
Well, simply that this is the kind of heroism

512
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:17,000
which it took Madgevars to.

513
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:23,000
They knew that there were people going to try and assassinate them.

514
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:31,000
She was beaten so badly that a few years later she died of her injuries.

515
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:37,000
And of course those three who were not just killed,

516
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:45,000
but terribly beaten before they were killed.

517
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:52,000
They finally got their evidence on the man who organized the killing.

518
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:58,000
Actually, there was an FBI man there the whole time.

519
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:06,000
And he could have probably did go to J. Edgar Hoover

520
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:15,000
and said, but who said oh they're probably all communists anyway.

521
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:19,000
Well let me thank you so much for welcoming us and allowing us to visit.

522
00:57:19,000 --> 00:57:21,000
It's really been a privilege to be with you.

523
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:23,000
Thank you.

524
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:26,000
And you're hot.

525
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:31,000
I'll take the.

526
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:33,000
It's just lovely.

527
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:42,000
It's been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

